It was also verified that people, after remembering or presence of anti-ethical acts, tend to wash their hands more frequently than others, and usually give more importance to equipment to wash their hands.
Moreover, those who can wash their hands after such a vision are less likely to perform other compensatory actions of "cleanness", such as volunteering.
The religions prescribe the washing of hands for hygienic and symbolic purposes. The symbolic washing of hands, using water, but not soap, to wash hands is part of a ritual washing of the hands characteristic in many religions, including Bahá'i faith, Hinduism, Tevilah and Netilat yadayim in Judaism, the washing of Christianity, and the abolition of Islamism. The religions also indicate the hygiene of the hands, especially after some actions.
